OOPs in Python (Object-Oriented Programming)
Object-Oriented Programming (OOP) is a programming style where code is organized using objects and classes.
Python supports OOP to help make programs:
• Reusable
• Organized
• Easy to maintain

1. Class and Object
   A class is a blueprint.
   An object is a real instance of the class.

• Constructor (**init**): A special method that is automatically called when an object is created.
• self: Refers to the current object of the class.
• Encapsulation: Wrapping data and methods into a single unit (class) and restricting direct access to data.
• Inheritance: The process by which one class acquires the properties and methods of another class.
• Polymorphism: The ability of the same method or function to behave differently for different objects.
• Abstraction: Hiding implementation details and showing only essential features to the user.
• Method: A function defined inside a class.
• Attribute: A variable that belongs to a class or object.
• Instance Variable: A variable whose value is unique for each object.
• Class Variable: A variable shared by all objects of a class.
• Public Member: Accessible from anywhere.
• Protected Member: Intended to be accessed within the class and its subclasses (prefixed with \_).
• Private Member: Accessible only within the class (prefixed with \_\_).
